The paper deals with motion planning for a collection of agents, specifically quadrotors, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). The use of a hierarchical framework for motion planning suggests a focus on multi-agent systems (cs.MA) and the need for coordination between agents. The paper also mentions the use of rules for constructing higher level motion primitives, which could indicate a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) techniques. Finally, the experimental results demonstrate the ability to maintain a formation while navigating a cluttered environment, which suggests a focus on control systems (cs.SY).
